    <stitle>VT 275 Engine Diagnostics Manual - Electronic Control Systems Diagnostics - Circuit Diagnostics - GPC (Glow
        Plug Control) Circuit
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc id="s305010706.21" svcproctype="diagnose" graphiccount="4">
        <title>GPC (Glow Plug Control) Circuit</title>
        <svcprocinfo id="s305010706.21.1">
            <figure id="f305010797" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figj31/J31199.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="432px"
                         scalefitheight="272px"/>
                <caption>Function diagram for the Glow Plug Control (GPC)</caption>
            </figure>
            <para id="s305010706.19.1.1"></para>
            <table id="t3050107198" type="simple" frame="topbot">
                <title>The function diagram for the Glow Plug Control system includes the following:</title>
                <tgroup cols="1">
                    <colspec colname="col1"/>
                    <tbody>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Glow plugs</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Glow plug relay</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Electronic Control Module (ECM)</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Engine Coolant Temperature sensor (ECT)</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Barometric Absolute Pressure sensor (BAP)</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Battery</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>WAIT TO START lamp</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                    </tbody>
                </tgroup>
            </table>
            <para>
                <title>Function</title>The glow plug control system warms the engine cylinders to aid cold engine
                starting and reduce exhaust emissions during warm-up.
            </para>
            <para>The ECM is programmed to energize the glow plugs (through the glow plug relay) while monitoring
                certain programmed conditions for engine coolant temperature and atmospheric pressure.
            </para>
            <para>The ECM monitors battery voltage, Barometric Absolute Pressure (BAP) sensor and Engine Coolant
                Temperature (ECT) sensor to determine the amount of time that the WAIT TO START lamp and glow plugs are
                on.
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>The WAIT TO START lamp on time is independent from the glow plug relay on time.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <para>The WAIT TO START lamp indicates when the glow plugs have been on long enough to start the engine. The
                on time normally varies between 2 to 10 seconds.
            </para>
            <para>The engine is ready to start when the WAIT TO START lamp is turned off by the ECM. The glow plugs can
                remain on up to 120 seconds while the engine is running to reduce exhaust emissions during engine
                warm-up.
            </para>
            <para>The glow plugs are self limiting and do not require cycling on and off. The glow plug relay will only
                cycle on and off repeatedly if system voltage is greater than 14.0 volts.
            </para>
            <para>Glow plugs are activated for a longer time, if the engine is cold or the barometric pressure is low
                (high altitude).
            </para>
        </svcprocinfo>
        <svcsubproc id="s305010706.21.2">
            <title>GPC Circuit Operation</title>
            <figure id="f305010798" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figj31/J31200.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="392px"
                         scalefitheight="532px"/>
                <caption>GPC Circuit Diagram</caption>
            </figure>
            <para>The glow plug control system operation on time is dependent upon the ECT, BAP, and battery voltage.
                The glow plug relay is activated by power supplied by the ECM through Pin X1-17 to the Glow Plug Control
                (GPC) circuit. The coil of the glow plug relay is grounded through the actuator power ground circuit,
                Pin 4 of the 12-pin connector to the battery negative terminal. Power is supplied to the switch side of
                the glow plug relay from the starter motor. When the relay coil is energized, power is supplied to the
                glow plugs that are grounded through the cylinder head.
            </para>
            <para>The ECM monitors the output of the relay, from the relay to Pin X1-21.</para>
            <para>The WAIT TO START lamp time is transmitted over the CAN1 datalink. See the applicable truck Service
                Manual.
            </para>
            <para>
                <title>Fault Detection/Management</title>The ECM continuously monitors the output of the Glow Plug
                relay, when voltage is not as expected a DTC will be set.
            </para>
            <para>An open or short to ground in the glow plug relay control circuit can be detected by an on demand
                Output Circuit Check (OCC) performed during the KOEO Standard test. When a circuit fault is detected, a
                DTC will be set. Glow plug and glow plug harness problems can not be detected by the ECM.
            </para>
            <para>
                <title>Glow Plug Control DTCs</title>DTCs are read using the EST or by counting the flashes from the
                amber and red lamps.
            </para>
            <table id="t3050107199" tblwidth="col-wide" type="simple" frame="topbot">
                <title>DTC 251</title>
                <tgroup cols="1">
                    <colspec colname="col1" colwidth="1.0*"/>
                    <tbody>
                        <row>
                            <entry>
                                <para>Glow Plug Control OCC self-test failed</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>DTC 251 is set by the ECM when the OCC test has failed after the KOEO Standard
                                    test has been run.
                                </para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>DTC 251 can be set for an open or shorted GPC signal circuit, an open actuator
                                    power ground, or an open glow plug relay coil.
                                </para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                    </tbody>
                </tgroup>
            </table>
            <table id="t3050107200" tblwidth="col-wide" type="simple" frame="topbot">
                <title>DTC 375</title>
                <tgroup cols="1">
                    <colspec colname="col1" colwidth="1.0*"/>
                    <tbody>
                        <row>
                            <entry>
                                <para>Glow Plug Relay Circuit Fault</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>DTC 375 is set by the ECM when the relay output voltage does not meet expected
                                    voltage.
                                </para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>DTC 375 can be set by an open in the B+ supply circuit to the glow plug relay,
                                    open or shorted GPD circuit, or failed glow plug relay.
                                </para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry>
                                <para>DTC 375 can be set if there is a failed control circuit, repair DTC 251 first.
                                </para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                    </tbody>
                </tgroup>
            </table>
